earts, O'Nell draws on recent anthropological theory to locate Flathead depression in the culturally organized experiences of an oppressed people. According to O'Nell, Flathead narratives of depression are tales in which narrators use their demoralization as a guide for modern Indian life. Underlying their tales, she says, is the dramatic assertion that depression is the natural condition of "real Indians"—those who have "disciplined" their hearts by recasting their personal sadness into compassion for others.This rich account of family and community life describes the moral imagination with which Flathead Indian people weave together historical and personal loss, American Indian identity, and social responsibility. Based on her ethnographic and clinical work, O'Nell pinpoints American Indian depression within a complex interplay of cultural ideas of the self and the Indian family, emotion and ethnic identity, and historical relations between Indians and whites.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural psychiatryxMontanaxFlathead Indian Reservation. 0aCultural psychiatryzMontanazFlathead Indian Reservation. 0aDepression, MentalxMontanaxFlathead Indian Reservation. 0aDepression, MentalzMontanazFlathead Indian Reservation. 0aEthnopsychologyxMontanaxFlathead Indian Reservation. 0aEthnopsychologyzMontanazFlathead Indian Reservation. 0aSalish IndiansxEthnic identity. 0aSalish IndiansxMental health. 0aSalish IndiansxPsychology. 4aAnthropology. 4aGeneral. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aDeLeane O’Nell, Theresa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021446040uhttps:/